    "body": "Hi everyone. I think getting Foundry in docker would be really helpful for both myself and others. Pushing forward off of what was built by others in #914 and #981 , I've made good progress in building a fully functioning, alpine based Foundry image. I think we should clarify next steps here in the issue rather than the pr.\r\n\r\nHere's what we have:\r\n- A Dockerfile that builds foundry from scratch on alpine: https://github.com/dmfxyz/foundry/blob/dockerize/Dockerfile. I have a build hosted in [ghcr right now](https://github.com/dmfxyz/foundry/pkgs/container/foundry/17170188?tag=dockerize). Final compressed image size is 20.9MB, pretty good IMO. Extracted is 42.9MB. \r\n\r\n- A github action that can cross build docker images for all architectures (currently just amd64 to save testing time): https://github.com/dmfxyz/foundry/blob/dockerize/.github/workflows/docker-publish.yml. The image is also signed.\r\n\r\nHere's some open questions/issues\r\n\r\n- I want to confirm there is still agreement among maintainers and community that we want a Docker image?\r\n\r\n- How should this be incorporated into CI/CD? I tend to agree with what was suggested in #914 by @onbjerg and have the release workflow call out to the multi-architecture build job I linked above.\r\n\r\n- The image will not build natively on neither Intel nor M1 macs based on my testing. I've THINK I narrowed it down to some libusb dependencies which are not able to be built because macos doesn't natively have libusb, and the brew install doesn't play nice with Docker (let me stress this is just a theory, it's a real rabbit hole). **_Good news is that an image built on, say, Ubuntu or some other *nix seems to run perfectly on both intel and m1 macs_** (I've tested on the two I own). In my experience this is a classic issue with building alpine based docker images on macos. Unless there are serious concerns with this, I don't think it's a first-release blocker as the release image will not be built on macos anyway. It is tech debt though. \r\n\r\n@gakonst @onbjerg @tynes @mattsse when you guys have time (I know there's a lot going on right now) please share your thoughts here. I'll get everything working as I have now, and then happy to put it on ice until we have time to answer the above. \r\n\r\nMany thanks to @abdulrabbani00 for getting this started. \r\n\r\n\r\n",
